Sue- tonius) to Vergil, was in circulation in the later years of Augustus, and known to Seneca (750-—818=4 B.C.——65 A.D.) either as a young man or in middle age, i.e. in the reigns of Tiberius (14—37)‚ Caligula (37-41), Claudius (41—511), is it likely that he would wholly have ignored it when writing to Lucilius on this very subject in the reign of Nero? This argument becomes stronger when we remember that Seneca, in the passage quoted above from Epist. 79, is speaking of poetical, not prose, descriptions of the volcano, Lucilius is to ascend Aetna and observe with his own eyes what he is then to describe in his promised poem. But if our Aetna was already familiarly known, or if it was known at all, how could it escape either Seneca or Lucilius, both of them poets, both, which is more to our purpose, keen explorcrs of natural phenomena?
